00:16:40,127 --> 00:16:44,803
- [Gunshot]
- [Tourists Screaming]

208
00:16:44,887 --> 00:16:49,517
Ladies and gentlemen, you're
being detained against your
will. For that I apologize.

209
00:16:49,607 --> 00:16:52,280
<i>It is not our intention</i>
<i>in any way to harm you.</i>

210
00:16:52,367 --> 00:16:55,598
You will not be detained one
minute longer than is necessary
for us to complete our mission.

211
00:17:01,767 --> 00:17:04,122
[Evac Commander]
Attention on deck!

212
00:17:04,207 --> 00:17:06,357
[Sighs]
Stand easy, men.

213
00:17:07,847 --> 00:17:11,476
Make no mistake about it, gentlemen.
We are now in harm's way.

214
00:17:11,567 --> 00:17:15,526
For Major Baxter and I, this is the last
campaign in a career dating back...

215
00:17:15,607 --> 00:17:17,438
to Tet '68.

216
00:17:17,527 --> 00:17:20,803
Likewise for Captain Hendrix
and Gunnery Sergeant Crisp,

217
00:17:20,887 --> 00:17:24,562
<i>who cut their teeth</i>
<i>under my command in Desert Storm.</i>

218
00:17:24,647 --> 00:17:27,559
Capt. Frye, Capt. Darrow, this is my
first operational situation with you...

219
00:17:27,647 --> 00:17:30,764
<i>and your men, and I have to say thus far</i>
<i>your conduct reflects your reputations.</i>

220
00:17:30,847 --> 00:17:32,678
- Thank you, General.
- Thank you, sir.

221
00:17:32,767 --> 00:17:36,203
We have achieved our position
through poise, precision and audacity.

222
00:17:36,287 --> 00:17:38,243
To this we must
now add resolve.

223
00:17:38,327 --> 00:17:41,637
We'll be branded as traitors;
the gravest capital crime.

224
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:44,844
Punishable by death.

225
00:17:44,927 --> 00:17:48,886
Couple hundred years ago, a few guys
named Washington, Jefferson and Adams...

226
00:17:48,967 --> 00:17:52,846
were branded as traitors
by the British.

227
00:17:52,927 --> 00:17:55,566
And now they're called
patriots.

228
00:17:55,647 --> 00:17:57,603
In time, so shall we.

229
00:17:59,367 --> 00:18:03,246
God willing, in less than 48 hours we
will evacuate this island in gunships...

230
00:18:03,327 --> 00:18:06,842
under cover of hostages
and VX gas warheads.

231
00:18:06,927 --> 00:18:10,124
Your destination:
a nonextradition-treaty country.

232
00:18:10,207 --> 00:18:14,678
<i>You will each be paid a fee</i>
<i>of $ 1 million for services rendered.</i>

233
00:18:14,767 --> 00:18:18,237
But you can never again
set foot on your native soil.

234
00:18:18,327 --> 00:18:22,115
- Can you live with that?
- [All] Yes, sir!

235
00:18:22,207 --> 00:18:24,846
The men of Marine Force Recon
are selected...

236
00:18:24,927 --> 00:18:28,840
to carry out illegal operations
throughout the world.

237
00:18:28,927 --> 00:18:34,479
When they don't come home, their
families are told fairy tales
about what happened to them...

238
00:18:34,567 --> 00:18:37,639
<i>and denied compensation.</i>

239
00:18:37,727 --> 00:18:41,037
Well, I have choked
on these lies my entire career.

240
00:18:41,127 --> 00:18:43,516
Well, here and now
the lies stop!

241
00:18:49,087 --> 00:18:52,716
God be with all of you.
Man your positions, men.

242
00:18:53,887 --> 00:18:56,560
<i>[Phone Ringing, Receiver Clanking]</i>

243
00:18:56,647 --> 00:18:58,763
This is FBI Director Womack.

244
00:18:58,847 --> 00:19:02,203
Director... be advised,

245
00:19:02,287 --> 00:19:05,006
81... I say again,

246
00:19:05,087 --> 00:19:08,762
81 civilians are under my control
as of this moment.

247
00:19:08,847 --> 00:19:12,920
<i>You are to take measures to assure this</i>
<i>remains a need-to-know classified fact.</i>

248
00:19:13,007 --> 00:19:17,046
- Who is this?
- Mr Director, you have
a very serious problem.

249
00:19:17,127 --> 00:19:20,164
A battery of VX gas rockets
is presently deployed to deliver...

250
00:19:20,247 --> 00:19:24,763
a highly lethal strike on the population
of the San Francisco Bay area.

251
00:19:24,847 --> 00:19:26,678
I will call again at 0100 hours
to state my demands.

252
00:19:26,767 --> 00:19:29,235
- I wanna know who I'm talking to.
- This is Brigadier General...

253
00:19:29,327 --> 00:19:33,559
- Francis X. Hummel, United States
Marine Corps from Alcatraz... out.
<i>- [Receiver Slams]</i>

254
00:19:34,607 --> 00:19:36,996
I'll cancel
your reservations.

255
00:19:37,087 --> 00:19:40,159
Get the Pentagon and call
the San Francisco office.

256
00:19:40,247 --> 00:19:43,364
It seems Alcatraz
was just reopened.

257
00:19:43,527 --> 00:19:47,236
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Last night, Gen. Hummel using</i>
<i>brutal but nonlethal force...</i>

258
00:19:47,327 --> 00:19:52,355
under the guise of
a security exercise, walked off
with 15 VX poison-gas rockets.

259
00:19:52,447 --> 00:19:54,358
<i>He lost one of his own men</i>
<i>in the process.</i>

260
00:19:54,447 --> 00:19:58,042
That's Gen. Hummel in Vietnam.
I think he was a major at the time.

261
00:19:58,127 --> 00:20:02,166
<i>Three tours in Vietnam,</i>
<i>Panama, Grenada, Desert Storm; :</i>

262
00:20:02,247 --> 00:20:06,718
<i>three Purple Hearts, two Silver Stars</i>
<i>and the Congressional Medal of...</i>

263
00:20:06,807 --> 00:20:09,275
Jesus. This man is a hero.

264
00:20:09,367 --> 00:20:12,439
Well, I think "legend" might be
a better description, Mr Sinclair.

265
00:20:12,527 --> 00:20:16,042
Well, now we can add kidnapping
and extortion to his list of accolades.

266
00:20:16,127 --> 00:20:18,243
<i>Mr Sinclair,</i>
<i>Gen. Hummel is a man of honour.</i>

267
00:20:19,727 --> 00:20:23,436
General, it's him.

268
00:20:23,527 --> 00:20:27,122
- Frank, it's Al Kramer.
- Hi, Al. How ya doin'?

269
00:20:27,207 --> 00:20:29,482
I don't know, Frank.
Why don't you tell me?

270
00:20:29,567 --> 00:20:32,286
There are a lot of very,
very worried people here, Frank.

271
00:20:32,367 --> 00:20:34,517
I'll come straight
to the point.

272
00:20:34,607 --> 00:20:37,599
Eighty-three Force
Reconnaissance Marines have died
under my various commands.

273
00:20:37,687 --> 00:20:39,962
Forty-seven in Northern Laos
and Southern China.

274
00:20:40,047 --> 00:20:43,119
Southern China? We never admitted
we sent troops into China.

275
00:20:43,207 --> 00:20:45,357
Who is this?
Identify yourself.

276
00:20:45,447 --> 00:20:48,200
White House Chief of Staff
Hayden Sinclair, General.

277
00:20:48,287 --> 00:20:51,597
How old are you,
Chief of Staff Sinclair?

278
00:20:51,687 --> 00:20:54,121
- I'm 33.
<i>- Well, Mr Sinclair,</i>

279
00:20:54,207 --> 00:20:56,960
you've probably got no fucking idea
what I'm talking about.

280
00:20:57,047 --> 00:20:59,356
By your ninth birthday
I was runnin' black ops into China,

281
00:20:59,447 --> 00:21:02,325
and my men were responsible
for over 200 enemy kills.

282
00:21:02,407 --> 00:21:05,240
Now put some rigging tape
over Mr Sinclair's mouth.

283
00:21:05,327 --> 00:21:08,603
- He's wasting my time.
- Ah, you want to continue, Frank?

284
00:21:08,687 --> 00:21:10,723
Remember Operation
Desert Storm?

285
00:21:10,807 --> 00:21:14,482
Those surgical hits made by our
smart bombs covered so well on CNN?

286
00:21:14,567 --> 00:21:19,038
<i>It was my men on the ground</i>
<i>that made those hits possible</i>
<i>by lasing the targets.</i>

287
00:21:19,127 --> 00:21:22,437
<i>Twenty of them were left</i>
<i>to rot outside Baghdad</i>
<i>after the conflict ended.</i>

288
00:21:22,527 --> 00:21:26,406
No benefits were paid to their
families. No medals conferred.

289
00:21:28,407 --> 00:21:32,320
These men died for their country
and they weren't even given
a goddam military burial.

290
00:21:34,647 --> 00:21:36,842
The situation
is unacceptable.

291
00:21:36,927 --> 00:21:40,397
<i>You will transfer $ 100 million</i>
<i>from the Grand Cayman Red Sea</i>
<i>Trading Company account...</i>

292
00:21:40,487 --> 00:21:42,318
<i>to an account I designate.</i>

293
00:21:42,407 --> 00:21:44,967
From these funds, reparations
of $ 1 million will be paid...

294
00:21:45,047 --> 00:21:47,561
to each of
the 83 marines' families.

295
00:21:47,647 --> 00:21:51,037
<i>The rest of the funds</i>
<i>I will disperse at my discretion.</i>

296
00:21:51,127 --> 00:21:53,243
Do I make myself clear?

297
00:21:53,327 --> 00:21:56,478
Except for the Red Sea
Trading Company. What is that?

298
00:21:56,567 --> 00:21:59,479
- Identify yourself.
- This is FBI Director Womack, General.

299
00:21:59,567 --> 00:22:03,037
It's a slush fund where the Pentagon
keeps proceeds from illegal arms sales.

300
00:22:03,127 --> 00:22:05,561
Jesus, Frank!
This is classified information.

301
00:22:05,647 --> 00:22:09,117
You alert the media,
I launch the gas.

302
00:22:09,207 --> 00:22:11,880
You refuse payment,
I launch the gas.

303
00:22:11,967 --> 00:22:15,755
You've got 40 hours...
till noon, day after tomorrow...
to arrange transfer of the money.

304
00:22:15,847 --> 00:22:19,522
I am aware of your countermeasure.
You know and I know
it doesn't stand a chance.

305
00:22:19,607 --> 00:22:21,677
- Hummel from Alcatraz, out.
<i>- [Receiver Slams]</i>

306
00:22:23,407 --> 00:22:25,238
<i>[Womack]</i>
<i>All right.</i>

307
00:22:25,327 --> 00:22:28,205
<i>We have to identify the hostages</i>
<i>and contact each of their families.</i>

308
00:22:28,287 --> 00:22:31,916
Tell 'em somethin'. Make up a story,
and we've got to keep this undercover.

309
00:22:32,007 --> 00:22:36,046
If this comes out, the city of
San Francisco will be in chaos.
I am talking anarchy.

310
00:22:36,127 --> 00:22:39,517
Wait a minute, wait a minute.
What is the potential casualty rate...

311
00:22:39,607 --> 00:22:43,680
for a single rocket armed
with VX poison gas, Gen. Peterson?

312
00:22:43,767 --> 00:22:45,598
Sixty or seventy.

313
00:22:45,687 --> 00:22:47,643
Well, that's...
that's not so bad.

314
00:22:47,727 --> 00:22:51,720
Thousand.
Seventy thousand dead.

315
00:22:51,807 --> 00:22:54,275
- Oh.
- One teaspoon of this hits the floor,

316
00:22:54,367 --> 00:22:56,927
it's lethal up to...
100 feet.

317
00:22:57,007 --> 00:23:00,761
One teaspoon of this shit
detonated in the atmosphere...

318
00:23:00,847 --> 00:23:03,441
will kill every living organism
in an eight-block radius.

319
00:23:03,527 --> 00:23:05,961
Get the point?

320
00:23:06,047 --> 00:23:08,515
What did Hummel mean by
your "countermeasure," General?

321
00:23:08,607 --> 00:23:12,316
Standard poison is countered
by napalm. It burns it up,
consumes it upon detonation.

322
00:23:12,407 --> 00:23:16,241
<i>Now, the problem with VX poison gas</i>
<i>is that it's designed specifically...</i>

323
00:23:16,327 --> 00:23:19,558
to withstand napalm; that's
where thermite plasma comes in.

324
00:23:19,647 --> 00:23:22,844
- Gen. Peterson?
- Thermite plasma incendiary systems...

325
00:23:22,927 --> 00:23:25,919
<i>can burn hot enough to consume VX,</i>
<i>but they're still in the test phase.</i>

326
00:23:26,007 --> 00:23:29,636
It's not operational.
Hummel knows this.

327
00:23:29,727 --> 00:23:33,197
- We are dealing with
one smart son of a bitch.
- What's it going to take...

328
00:23:33,287 --> 00:23:37,917
to equip a flight of F-18s
with thermite plasma
within the next 36 hours?

329
00:23:38,007 --> 00:23:41,317
- An act of God.
- Excuse me?

330
00:23:41,407 --> 00:23:43,238
All right. We can try.

331
00:23:43,327 --> 00:23:46,922
But I strongly urge you to consider the
use of this as a secondary initiative.

332
00:23:47,007 --> 00:23:49,919
Then we have to go to our
primary initiative. Uh, Admiral?

333
00:23:50,007 --> 00:23:53,397
Sir, I'd like to bring in our SEAL
ground commander, Cmdr. Anderson.

334
00:23:53,487 --> 00:23:58,003
Mr Womack, who is your best
chemical/biological man?

335
00:23:58,167 --> 00:24:00,397
<i>- [Creaking]</i>
<i>- [Stanley, Grunting]</i>
<i>That's interesting.</i>

336
00:24:00,487 --> 00:24:03,320
- Oh, yeah.
<i>- That's very compelling.</i>

337
00:24:03,407 --> 00:24:05,841
[Both Moaning]

338
00:24:05,927 --> 00:24:08,395
Ahh, you like my pigtails?

339
00:24:08,487 --> 00:24:11,365
Oh, yeah.
Pigtails are naughty.

340
00:24:11,447 --> 00:24:14,280
- Naughty, naughty...
- [Moans]

341
00:24:14,367 --> 00:24:17,006
You're just an amaretto cream
with peach sorbet persuasion.

342
00:24:17,087 --> 00:24:19,840
<i>- [Phone Rings]</i>
- This isn't happening.

343
00:24:19,927 --> 00:24:22,077
- [Breathlessly]
No, Stan. Don't answer it.
- This isn't happening!

344
00:24:22,167 --> 00:24:24,601
- No, just don't answer it. It's okay.
- I have to.

345
00:24:24,687 --> 00:24:26,564
- It's the office, baby.
They know I'm home.
- Oh-h-h-h!

346
00:24:26,647 --> 00:24:30,686
- How could they possibly know
that you're home?
- It's the FBI.

347
00:24:30,767 --> 00:24:33,281
<i>[Ringing Stops, Receiver Clicks]</i>

348
00:24:33,367 --> 00:24:36,439
- Stanley! Tsk!
- Goodspeed.

349
00:24:36,527 --> 00:24:39,166
Yeah. Okay. Yeah, I'll be...
I'll be down...

350
00:24:39,247 --> 00:24:42,159
- Yeah, downstairs in ten minutes.
- No, you won't.

351
00:24:42,247 --> 00:24:44,681
<i>[Phone Beeps Off]</i>

352
00:24:44,767 --> 00:24:48,476
- I have to go to San Francisco.
- No, you don't.

353
00:24:48,567 --> 00:24:51,957
Stanley. No, you do not have
to go to San Francisco.

354
00:24:52,047 --> 00:24:54,402
Are you kidding me? Right now, you need
stay here and talk to me about things.

355
00:24:54,487 --> 00:24:57,320
- I've got to go, baby.
- [Disgusted Groan] I am Catholic.

356
00:24:57,407 --> 00:24:59,443
Do you realize that?
I am pregnant and I am unmarried...

357
00:24:59,527 --> 00:25:02,200
and this causes
a serious problem for me.

358
00:25:02,287 --> 00:25:04,403
I cannot believe you.

359
00:25:07,087 --> 00:25:09,726
[Sighs]

360
00:25:12,967 --> 00:25:14,798
N-N-No.

361
00:25:14,887 --> 00:25:18,402
- [Kissing Sounds]
- I love you.

362
00:25:18,487 --> 00:25:22,719
I will marry you.
I just didn't plan on this, that's all.

363
00:25:22,807 --> 00:25:25,605
- [Relieved Laugh]
- Come to San Francisco.

364
00:25:25,687 --> 00:25:28,679
- Really?
- Yeah. I'm sure it's just
a training exercise.

365
00:25:28,767 --> 00:25:30,997
Check into the hotel,
order up some champagne...

366
00:25:31,087 --> 00:25:33,043
- And we'll finish what we started?
- Exactly.

367
00:25:33,127 --> 00:25:35,925
- Baby, you gonna marry me?
- You know it.

368
00:25:36,007 --> 00:25:38,840
[Laughing]
You're gonna marry me!
Oh, honey, come on.

369
00:25:38,927 --> 00:25:41,122
- Just a really quick one.
- [Groaning] Oh! Oh! I gotta go!

370
00:25:41,207 --> 00:25:44,165
A nighttime airdrop incursion
is out, due to the full moon.

371
00:25:44,247 --> 00:25:46,124
Likewise a frontal
seaside attack.

372
00:25:46,207 --> 00:25:49,324
If we're compromised and shots
are fired, Hummel might launch.

373
00:25:49,407 --> 00:25:52,001
Our only alternative is an attack
from within the prison.

374
00:25:52,087 --> 00:25:55,443
<i>We penetrate the island through</i>
<i>the tunnels under the prison</i>
<i>buildings undetected...</i>

375
00:25:55,527 --> 00:25:57,836
<i>and emerge in its centre; : that way,</i>
<i>we can jump the marines from behind.</i>

376
00:25:57,927 --> 00:26:02,045
And if we're lucky, take their
rocket positions without a shot fired.

377
00:26:02,127 --> 00:26:05,517
- I don't understand. You-You've
studied the architectural plans?
- They're useless.

378
00:26:05,607 --> 00:26:10,203
Alcatraz has been ripped up
and rebuilt for years.
Under there is a maze of shit.

379
00:26:10,287 --> 00:26:13,802
There's no question, gentlemen.
We need firsthand intelligence
of the tunnel systems.

380
00:26:13,887 --> 00:26:16,481
- So what about the former warden?
- Died in 1979.

381
00:26:16,567 --> 00:26:19,240
All the guards
we contacted were useless.

382
00:26:19,327 --> 00:26:23,525
Umm... there is someone who,
I think, can help us.

383
00:26:26,807 --> 00:26:28,923
This is for the sake
of national security.

384
00:26:29,007 --> 00:26:33,398
No, it's the sake of national
security that got us here
in the first place 33 years ago.

385
00:26:33,487 --> 00:26:36,797
I knew... I knew someday this would
come back to bite us. Forget it.

386
00:26:36,887 --> 00:26:39,765
- He does not exist.
- He does exist!

387
00:26:39,847 --> 00:26:43,317
We just chose to forget him
for 30 years. We locked him
up and threw away the key.

388
00:26:43,407 --> 00:26:45,557
Oh, and a lot of
goddam good it did us.

389
00:26:45,647 --> 00:26:48,639
He broke out of two maximum security
prisons, and if he hits the streets...

390
00:26:48,727 --> 00:26:50,957
He's not gonna "hit the streets," Jim!
[Chuckles]

391
00:26:51,047 --> 00:26:53,959
Thirty years ago he was
a highly-trained SAS operative.

392
00:26:54,047 --> 00:26:58,598
He is my age now, for Christ's
sake. I have to get up three
times a night to take a piss.

393
00:26:58,687 --> 00:27:01,042
[Quietly]
We can't risk letting him out.

394
00:27:01,127 --> 00:27:03,960
<i>He's a professional escape artist.</i>

395
00:27:10,287 --> 00:27:12,482
<i>[Lock Turning, Door Opening]</i>

396
00:27:34,607 --> 00:27:37,041
[Womack]
Oh, here is now.

397
00:27:37,127 --> 00:27:39,436
- Ah. Neat, uh...
- Yeah.

398
00:27:39,527 --> 00:27:42,166
- Neat, neat plane.
- Dr Goodspeed. James Womack.

399
00:27:42,247 --> 00:27:44,078
- Pleasure meeting you, sir. Thank you.
- Welcome.

400
00:27:44,167 --> 00:27:46,965
You come very highly recommended.
BA, Columbia;

401
00:27:47,047 --> 00:27:49,117
MA, PhD,
Johns Hopkins.

402
00:27:49,207 --> 00:27:51,038
Biochemistry/ toxicology?

403
00:27:51,127 --> 00:27:53,721
Well, I'm one of those fortunate
people who like my job, sir.

404
00:27:53,807 --> 00:27:56,526
Got my first chemistry set when
I was seven. Blew my eyebrows off.

405
00:27:56,607 --> 00:27:59,440
We never saw the cat again.
Been into it ever since. [Chuckles]

406
00:27:59,527 --> 00:28:01,802
- What do you know about VX gas?
- Liquid.

407
00:28:01,887 --> 00:28:04,447
Failed pesticide discovered
by mistake in 1952.

408
00:28:04,527 --> 00:28:06,836
Uh, actually it's kind of
like champagne that way.
The Franciscan monks thought...

409
00:28:06,927 --> 00:28:09,725
they were making white wine, somehow
the bottle carbonated, voila, champagne,

410
00:28:09,807 --> 00:28:12,275
- and then the whole thing...
- The gas, Dr Goodspeed.

411
00:28:12,367 --> 00:28:16,883
It's very, very horrible, sir.
It's one of those things
we wish we could disinvent.

412
00:28:18,327 --> 00:28:20,318
This isn't
a training exercise, is it?

413
00:28:20,407 --> 00:28:24,685
No, Dr Goodspeed,
it's not a training exercise.

414
00:28:34,967 --> 00:28:37,197
[Man Clears Throat]

415
00:28:41,487 --> 00:28:43,318
